// DOMAIN QUIZ DATA — 15 questions per domain (75 total)
// Format: {q, opts[4], ans (0-indexed), exp}

const DOMAIN_QUIZZES = [

  // ── D1: Foundational Data Model (15 questions)
  [
    {q:"In the ServiceNow CSM B2B data model, which table stores Account records representing customer companies?",opts:["sys_account","customer_account","csm_account","core_company"],ans:1,exp:"Account records in CSM B2B are stored in the 'customer_account' table. This is distinct from sys_account (a ServiceNow platform-internal table) and core_company (the Companies table). The customer_account table is specific to the CSM application."},
    {q:"What is the primary distinction between a 'Sold Product' and a 'Product Model' in ServiceNow CSM?",opts:["They are identical objects with different display names","Product Model is the generic product definition; Sold Product is the record of a specific product sold to a specific customer","Sold Product is used in B2C only; Product Model is used in B2B only","Product Model is created by agents; Sold Product is created by customers"],ans:1,exp:"Product Model is the catalog-level definition of a product (name, specs, version). Sold Product is the transaction record linking a specific Product Model to a specific customer Account, capturing what was actually purchased. Sold Products feed into Install Base Item creation for tracking deployed instances."},
    {q:"Which entitlement type is BEST suited for a contract that grants a customer 40 hours of support per month, tracked by time consumed?",opts:["Allocated Entitlement","Product Entitlement","Time-Based Entitlement","Service Entitlement"],ans:2,exp:"Time-Based Entitlement tracks support entitlement in units of time (e.g., 40 hours/month). As agents log time against cases, the entitlement balance is decremented. Allocated Entitlement counts cases (not hours). Service Entitlement defines a service level without a cap.", diagram:"entitlement-types"},
    {q:"In the CSM Partner model, what role does a Partner account play relative to an end-customer Account?",opts:["A Partner is a subtype of Contact with elevated privileges","A Partner is a reseller or intermediary who can open and manage cases on behalf of end-customer Accounts","A Partner replaces the need for an Account Hierarchy","A Partner is a special Consumer type used in B2C scenarios"],ans:1,exp:"The Partner model allows authorized partner companies (e.g., resellers, system integrators) to open, update, and manage cases on behalf of their end-customers. The Partner Account is linked to the end-customer Account via an Account Relationship, giving partners a controlled view of their customers' cases."},
    {q:"Which table stores Consumer records in a ServiceNow CSM B2C implementation?",opts:["customer_contact","sys_user","csm_consumer","customer_account"],ans:2,exp:"Consumer records are stored in the 'csm_consumer' table. This is the B2C counterpart to the B2B customer_contact table. The csm_consumer table holds individual end-customer records that are not associated with any parent Account, unlike customer_contact which requires an Account linkage."},
    {q:"What does the 'Household' entity in ServiceNow CSM represent?",opts:["A grouping of related Account records in a B2B hierarchy","A B2C entity that groups multiple Consumers living at the same address under one household unit","A type of Contact used for residential customers","A container for multiple Install Base Items at one location"],ans:1,exp:"The Household entity is a B2C concept that groups Consumer records belonging to the same household (e.g., family members at the same address). It allows a utility or telecom company to associate multiple individual Consumers under one household, enabling household-level case and entitlement management.", diagram:"household-b2c"},
    {q:"A Product Entitlement in CSM verification is typically triggered when:",opts:["A customer opens any case regardless of product","A case is linked to a specific Install Base Item or Sold Product covered by the entitlement","A contract is renewed automatically","A consumer logs into the Customer Service Portal"],ans:1,exp:"Product Entitlement verification checks whether the specific product referenced in the case (via Install Base Item or Sold Product) is covered under an active entitlement. If the case product does not match a covered product in the customer's entitlement, the verification fails and a warning is shown to the agent."},
    {q:"In ServiceNow CSM, an Account Relationship record is used to:",opts:["Link a Contact to their Account","Define the parent-child hierarchy between two Account records","Create a formal association between two different Account entities such as a partner or subsidiary link","Associate an Entitlement to an Account"],ans:2,exp:"Account Relationships define formal associations between two Account records — for example, a Partner-Customer relationship or a Competitor relationship. This is different from Account Hierarchy (parent-child ownership). Account Relationships use a configurable relationship type field."},
    {q:"When entitlement verification runs on a new case and finds NO matching entitlement, what is the CORRECT OOTB system behavior?",opts:["The case is automatically placed on hold and escalated to a billing team","The case creation is blocked and the agent must contact the billing department","A warning indicator appears on the case, but the agent can still save and proceed","The system creates a temporary one-time entitlement automatically"],ans:2,exp:"OOTB entitlement verification is non-blocking. When no valid entitlement is found, a warning indicator is displayed, but agents retain full ability to save and work the case. This behavior can be customized via configuration, but out of the box it is advisory only."},
    {q:"Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of Install Base Items in the CSM data model?",opts:["They represent future product purchases in the sales pipeline","They are catalog items available for customers to order","They track specific product instances actively deployed at a customer site, enabling product-specific case support","They are equivalent to CMDB Configuration Items and share the same table"],ans:2,exp:"Install Base Items (install_base_item table) represent the inventory of products actively deployed for a specific customer Account. Each item links a Product Model to an Account and captures deployment details. While Install Base Items can be related to CMDB CIs, they are not the same object."},
    {q:"A large company has a corporate parent account with subsidiaries in three countries. Each subsidiary needs separate case queues, but the parent should have visibility into all subsidiaries. What CSM feature supports this?",opts:["Multiple separate ServiceNow instances, one per country","Account Hierarchy with the parent Account and each subsidiary as a child Account","One flat Account with multiple Contact groups per country","Consumer Households mapped to each country"],ans:1,exp:"Account Hierarchy is the correct feature. The parent is the global Account, and each regional subsidiary is a child Account. Cases, entitlements, and contacts can be managed at the subsidiary level, while the parent account hierarchy gives executive visibility across all child accounts.", diagram:"account-hierarchy"},
    {q:"Which of the following statements about the customer_contact table is TRUE?",opts:["It stores records for both B2B Contacts and B2C Consumers","Contacts in this table must be linked to a record in the customer_account table","It is a direct extension of the sys_user table with no additional fields","Contacts stored here are automatically granted access to the Customer Service Portal"],ans:1,exp:"In the B2B data model, every Contact record in customer_contact must reference a parent Account in customer_account — the Account field is required. This mandatory linkage is what distinguishes a B2B Contact from a B2C Consumer. Contacts are not automatically granted portal access; that requires role assignment."},
    {q:"A company offers Silver (10 cases/year), Gold (50 cases/year), and Platinum (unlimited) support tiers. Which entitlement types are MOST appropriate?",opts:["Service Entitlement for all three tiers","Allocated Entitlement for Silver and Gold; Service Entitlement for Platinum","Time-Based Entitlement for Silver and Gold; Product Entitlement for Platinum","Product Entitlement for all three, with different allocation values"],ans:1,exp:"Silver (10 cases/year) and Gold (50 cases/year) are Allocated Entitlements — they define a maximum number of cases per period. Platinum (unlimited) is best represented as a Service Entitlement, which defines a service level without a case count cap."},
    {q:"In the ServiceNow CSM data model, which relationship exists between Contracts and Accounts?",opts:["One Contract can be shared across multiple unrelated Accounts","Each Contract is associated with exactly one Account, and an Account can have multiple Contracts","Contracts are associated with Contacts, not Accounts","Contracts are only linked to Install Base Items, not directly to Accounts"],ans:1,exp:"A Contract in CSM is linked to one specific customer Account. However, a single Account can have multiple Contracts (e.g., a hardware support contract and a software support contract). Each Contract can then have multiple Entitlements deriving validity from it."},
    {q:"An implementer notices that when agents create cases for a specific Account, no entitlement warning appears even though the Account has no active entitlements. What is the MOST likely cause?",opts:["Entitlement Verification is working correctly — no warning is expected","The Entitlement Verification business rule has been deactivated or is not configured for that Account's service","The Account has a hidden automatic entitlement created at Account setup","Entitlement Verification only runs for B2C Consumers, not B2B Accounts"],ans:1,exp:"The most likely cause is that the Entitlement Verification business rule has been deactivated, misconfigured, or has an incorrect filter condition. Entitlement Verification runs via a business rule — if it's disabled or has an incorrect scope, it silently skips verification. This is a common implementation oversight."}
  ],

  // ── D2: CSM Configuration (15 questions)
  [
    {q:"A company activates the CSM plugin on a fresh instance. The administrator notices that Advanced Work Assignment is not functioning. Which plugin must also be activated?",opts:["com.snc.agent_workspace","com.snc.advanced_work_assignment","com.glideapp.servicecatalog","com.snc.customer_service.b2c"],ans:1,exp:"Advanced Work Assignment (AWA) requires the 'com.snc.advanced_work_assignment' plugin to be separately activated. The CSM core plugin does not automatically enable AWA. The administrator must activate AWA as a distinct plugin, after which service channels, queues, and capacity configurations become available."},
    {q:"An AWA queue is configured for the Technical Support service channel. An agent has a capacity of 5 and currently holds 4 active cases. A new Priority 1 case arrives. What does AWA do?",opts:["It skips this agent entirely because P1 cases require a dedicated queue","It assigns the case to this agent because they are under capacity","It places the case on hold until the agent drops to 3 active cases","It escalates the case to the supervisor since the agent is near capacity"],ans:1,exp:"AWA checks agent capacity before assignment — if the agent's current workload (4) is below their defined maximum capacity (5), they are eligible to receive the new case regardless of its priority. Priority influences the ORDER in which queued work is offered to agents, not whether a below-capacity agent receives it."},
    {q:"A company wants agents to follow a structured, phase-driven resolution path for Data Breach cases — with different steps for Triage, Legal Review, and Customer Notification phases. Which CSM configuration tool builds this?",opts:["Flow Designer with subflows for each phase","Assignment Rules with group escalation","Process Automation Designer (PAD) to create a Playbook with lanes and phases","UI Builder workspace with conditional panels"],ans:2,exp:"Process Automation Designer (PAD) is the correct tool for CSM Playbooks. It supports phase-driven flows where each phase contains activities, and lanes define which team or role owns each activity. Flow Designer handles background automation but does not produce the structured, UI-visible Playbook experience.", diagram:"playbook-phases"},
    {q:"An implementer has built a Playbook in PAD and associated it with a Case Type. Agents report the Playbook never appears in the Agent Workspace. What is the MOST likely misconfiguration?",opts:["The Playbook is in Draft state and has not been published/activated","The Agent Workspace theme is set to Classic UI","The CSM-ITSM Bridge is blocking playbook activation","The case SLA is paused, which freezes all playbook activity"],ans:0,exp:"A Playbook must be in an Active/Published state in PAD for it to trigger on cases. A Playbook left in Draft will pass all trigger condition checks but will never surface in the Agent Workspace. This is one of the most common post-build oversights during CSM implementations."},
    {q:"A company uses CSM and ITSM on the same instance. A CSM agent creates an Incident from the case via the CSM-ITSM Bridge. When the Incident is resolved, what happens to the original Case automatically?",opts:["Nothing — the agent must manually update the Case","The Business Rule 'Update Case on Incident Closure' fires and updates the Case state","The Case is cloned with the Incident resolution notes","The Case is automatically closed and a CSAT survey is sent"],ans:1,exp:"The out-of-the-box Business Rule 'Update Case on Incident Closure' is the bidirectional sync mechanism in the CSM-ITSM Bridge. When the linked Incident moves to Resolved or Closed, this Business Rule fires and updates the parent Case state accordingly."},
    {q:"When configuring a Case Type in CSM, setting a 'Parent Case Type' field means the new Case Type:",opts:["Makes the parent Case Type automatically escalate to this new one","Inherits default field values, form sections, and SLA definitions from the parent unless overridden","Is restricted to child cases only — it cannot be used for standalone cases","Forces this Case Type to use the parent's Assignment Rules"],ans:1,exp:"Case Type hierarchy in CSM uses inheritance — a child Case Type inherits SLA definitions, form layouts, and default field values from its parent unless explicitly overridden. This allows implementers to define common behaviors at the parent level and customize only what differs at the child level."},
    {q:"A CSM administrator wants certain high-value accounts to display a persistent banner to agents with special handling instructions. Where is this configured?",opts:["Account record > Notes tab > Internal Instructions field","Customer Service > Special Handling Notes > create note linked to the Account","Agent Workspace > UI Builder > add a static banner component","System Properties > CSM > Executive Account Flag"],ans:1,exp:"Special Handling Notes are configured under Customer Service > Special Handling Notes. Each note is linked to a specific Account (or Contact) and automatically surfaces in the Agent Workspace when an agent opens a case for that customer. They support rich-text instructions."},
    {q:"A Walk-Up Experience kiosk is deployed in a corporate lobby. Which CSM module provides the queue management and check-in functionality?",opts:["Field Service Management dispatch board","CSM Walk-Up Experience with its dedicated queue and check-in interface","Advanced Work Assignment with walk-up as a service channel","Service Portal with a custom walk-up widget"],ans:1,exp:"The Walk-Up Experience is a dedicated CSM module that provides the customer-facing check-in interface (tablet/kiosk), queue position and wait time display, and the agent-facing workspace queue for handling walk-up interactions. It operates as its own service channel separate from digital channels."},
    {q:"An administrator is configuring a Service Definition for Cloud Platform Support. To ensure the case form automatically displays fields specific to cloud infrastructure (Region, Instance ID, Tier), what should the Service Definition include?",opts:["An association to a specialized Case Type with those custom fields","An Inbound Email Action triggered by the service name","A UI Policy on the default case form that checks the service description","An Assignment Rule that opens the correct form template"],ans:0,exp:"Associating a specialized Case Type with the Service Definition is the correct approach. The Case Type defines the form layout including custom fields. When a case is created for the service, the linked Case Type drives the form rendering, ensuring the right fields appear automatically."},
    {q:"During an AWA implementation, an agent's shift is configured as Mon–Fri 09:00–17:00. It is 16:55 on Friday and a new case arrives. The agent has 2 of 5 capacity slots used. What does AWA do?",opts:["Assigns the case to the agent since they are online and under capacity","Holds the case in queue until Monday 09:00","Routes the case to another agent whose shift extends past 17:00","Escalates the case immediately to the supervisor due to end-of-shift risk"],ans:2,exp:"AWA respects Shift configurations. An agent nearing the end of their shift window may be excluded from new assignments based on shift overlap rules, even if still online and under capacity. The queued case would be routed to another eligible agent whose shift covers the remaining time."},
    {q:"An operations manager wants phone calls to always be offered to agents before chat messages when both are waiting in AWA queues. Which AWA configuration controls this?",opts:["Set a higher SLA on phone cases — AWA reads SLA priority","Configure the Service Channel priority weighting in AWA — phone gets a higher priority value","Create an Assignment Rule that intercepts phone cases before AWA","Change the phone Inbound Email Action order"],ans:1,exp:"AWA Service Channel configuration includes a priority weighting setting. By assigning the phone service channel a higher priority value than chat, AWA will preferentially offer waiting phone interactions to available agents before chat messages. This is managed in the AWA Service Channel record."},
    {q:"A company deploys Engagement Messenger on their e-commerce website. A logged-in customer clicks the support widget and their account info is automatically pre-populated. What enables this seamless identity resolution?",opts:["The customer's browser cookie stores the ServiceNow session","Engagement Messenger uses a JWT (JSON Web Token) passed from the host website to authenticate and identify the customer","The customer must always log in separately to ServiceNow first","Engagement Messenger reads the customer's email from browser autofill"],ans:1,exp:"Engagement Messenger supports authenticated sessions via JWT token exchange. The host website passes a signed JWT containing the customer's identity to Engagement Messenger, which validates it and resolves the customer to their Consumer or Contact record in ServiceNow. This eliminates re-authentication."},
    {q:"A CSM scoped application needs to access tables in the sn_customerservice scope. Which setting must be verified?",opts:["The scoped app must be set to Global scope to access CSM tables","The Application Access settings on the CSM tables must allow cross-scope access from the scoped app","CSM tables are always available to all scopes by default","The developer must copy CSM tables into their own scope"],ans:1,exp:"In ServiceNow's scoped application model, cross-scope table access is controlled by Application Access settings on each table. CSM tables in the sn_customerservice scope must be configured to allow reads/writes from other scopes. These permissions are not open by default."},
    {q:"A CSM architect configures skills-based routing for a multilingual support team. Spanish-speaking cases must reach agents certified in Spanish. After enabling AWA, which configuration sequence is correct?",opts:["Create Assignment Rule > add language condition > assign to Spanish group > done","Define Skill 'Spanish Language' > assign to agents > configure AWA queue to require that skill > enable skill-based routing","Configure shift schedules first > then skills > then queues","Set a system property in CSM Properties, then AWA auto-discovers skills from user profiles"],ans:1,exp:"Skills-based routing in AWA requires: (1) creating the Skill record, (2) assigning that skill to eligible agents in their Agent Profile, and (3) configuring the AWA queue to require that skill as a routing attribute. Only then does AWA match incoming cases to qualified agents.", diagram:"awa-routing"},
    {q:"Which system property under Customer Service > Administration > Properties controls whether the CSM application uses condition-based Assignment Rules or capacity-aware AWA routing?",opts:["glide.cs.model.selector","glide.cs.awa.enabled","csm.routing.mode","sn_customerservice.assignment.type"],ans:1,exp:"The 'glide.cs.awa.enabled' system property in CSM Properties activates AWA-driven routing. When enabled, AWA takes over from static Assignment Rules for individual agent assignment, factoring in availability, capacity, skills, and shifts. Assignment Rules can still set the group; AWA then selects the best agent within that group."}
  ],

  // ── D3: Case Management (15 questions)
  [
    {q:"In the standard CSM case lifecycle, which state immediately follows 'New' when an agent begins actively working on the case?",opts:["Awaiting Info","In Progress","Open","Escalated"],ans:2,exp:"The standard CSM state flow is New > Open > Awaiting Info > Resolved > Closed. A case moves to 'Open' when an agent first acts on it. 'In Progress' is not a default state in the OOTB CSM case flow — 'Open' is the correct next state after New.", diagram:"case-state-flow"},
    {q:"Which prefix is assigned to Case Task numbers in ServiceNow CSM out of the box?",opts:["TASK","CSCASE","CSTASK","SCTASK"],ans:2,exp:"Case Tasks use the 'CSTASK' prefix (e.g., CSTASK0001234). This distinguishes them from platform Tasks (TASK prefix), Incident Tasks (ITASK), and Service Catalog Tasks (SCTASK). Recognizing the CSTASK prefix is a key identifier for Case Tasks."},
    {q:"An agent sets a case to 'Awaiting Info' and the SLA has a pause condition configured for that state. Three days later the customer replies. What happens to the SLA elapsed time during those three days?",opts:["The three days are added to the elapsed time and count toward breach","The SLA resets completely to zero when the case returns to Open","The three days are excluded from elapsed time — the SLA timer was paused","The SLA is automatically extended by three days without pausing"],ans:2,exp:"With a Pause Condition on Awaiting Info, the SLA timer stops accumulating elapsed time while the case is in that state. When the case returns to Open, the timer resumes from where it was before the pause. The customer delay does not count against the SLA target."},
    {q:"A support team identifies a cloud storage outage affecting 300 customers. A manager creates a Major Case record. What is the next required step?",opts:["Immediately send a Case Digest to all 300 customers","Submit the Major Case for approval — it must be approved before child cases can be linked","Set the Major Case to Resolved and reopen it","Create a new Targeted Communication campaign"],ans:1,exp:"Major Issue Management requires an approval step before the Major Case is activated. The record is flagged as a 'major case candidate' and routed through an approval workflow. Only after approval is it formally promoted to a Major Case, enabling child case linking and Case Digest communications.", diagram:"major-case-flow"},
    {q:"An agent is working on a case and notices it is structurally identical to another case (same account, same product, same issue). Which CSM feature should the agent use to consolidate them?",opts:["Case escalation via the Escalate Case UI action","Proactive Customer Service Operations merge workflow","Case merge — combining two cases into a single master case","Creating a parent-child Major Case relationship"],ans:2,exp:"Case merge allows combining duplicate or related cases into a single master case. The merged case is closed and its activities and notes are consolidated into the surviving case. This is different from Major Case parent-child linking, which is used for large outages affecting many customers."},
    {q:"In Major Issue Management, an agent wants to push resolution notes to all 200 linked child cases simultaneously. Which feature enables this?",opts:["Targeted Communications broadcast","Case Digest with resolution details","Parent-child synchronization — the Major Case resolution propagates to child cases via configured sync rules","Bulk case update via list editor"],ans:2,exp:"Parent-child case synchronization in Major Issue Management allows configuring which fields (including resolution notes, state, close notes) on the Major Case propagate down to linked child cases. This enables one resolution entry to update all affected child cases simultaneously."},
    {q:"An agent clicks the 'Escalate Case' UI action on a case record. What is the direct outcome?",opts:["The case is immediately assigned to the manager's queue","An escalation record is created and the case is flagged as escalated, notifying the designated escalation contact","The case SLA is automatically reset to its initial value","The case state changes to Awaiting Info pending escalation approval"],ans:1,exp:"The 'Escalate Case' UI action creates an escalation record linked to the case and marks the case as escalated. This triggers notifications to the escalation manager and changes the escalation flag on the case. It does not reset SLAs or change the case state to Awaiting Info."},
    {q:"A customer sends an email to support@company.com. ServiceNow automatically creates a new case from that email. Which configuration component is responsible?",opts:["Assignment Rule with email trigger","Business Rule on the email table","Inbound Email Action configured on the support mailbox","Scheduled Job that polls the mailbox"],ans:2,exp:"Inbound Email Actions process incoming emails and define what happens when an email arrives — including automatically creating a Case, populating fields from the email content, and linking the case to the sender's Contact record. This is the core email channel configuration in CSM."},
    {q:"A resolved case has been sitting in the Resolved state. The auto-close flow runs and the customer had not responded. What is the resulting case state?",opts:["Awaiting Info","Cancelled","Closed","Archived"],ans:2,exp:"The auto-close flow moves cases from Resolved to Closed after the configured waiting period. Closed is the final state in the standard CSM lifecycle. Cancelled and Archived are not standard auto-close destinations in the OOTB CSM flow."},
    {q:"A customer calls about a case that was recently closed. The agent verifies the issue has returned and sets the case state back to Open. What typically happens to the case number?",opts:["A new case number is always generated","The original case record and number is reused, and the SLA resets","The old case merges into a new one with a new number","The case is sent to a manager with the same number"],ans:1,exp:"Case reopening reuses the original case record and case number — no new case is created. When a closed case is reopened, it returns to an active state and SLA calculations reset, treating the renewal of the issue as a fresh SLA start while preserving the full case history."},
    {q:"A CSM administrator wants to proactively notify customers about a known product defect BEFORE they contact support. Which feature is specifically designed for this?",opts:["Case Digest on an active Major Case","Targeted Communications to a defined customer segment","Scheduled SLA breach notifications","Engagement Messenger broadcast mode"],ans:1,exp:"Targeted Communications is the CSM feature designed for proactive, segmented outreach — sending custom messages to specific groups of customers filtered by product, account, or entitlement tier. Case Digest is reactive (attached to an active Major Case). Targeted Communications supports proactive outreach independently."},
    {q:"Proactive Customer Service Operations (PCSO) in ServiceNow integrates with which other ServiceNow product to detect potential customer-impacting issues before customers call in?",opts:["HR Service Delivery","IT Operations Management (ITOM) — monitoring events and alerts","Governance, Risk and Compliance (GRC)","Financial Management for IT"],ans:1,exp:"Proactive Customer Service Operations connects CSM with ITOM. When ITOM detects an infrastructure event that could impact customers, PCSO can automatically create cases, notify affected customers via Targeted Communications, and link cases to the underlying ITOM event — all before customers call in."},
    {q:"A customer opens a case via the portal, calls the support line (agent adds a note), then sends a follow-up email — all for the same issue. Where are all these interactions visible together?",opts:["Three separate records: Portal Case, Phone Note, Email Case","Only the most recent interaction is shown in the workspace","The Case Activity Stream / Timeline shows all interactions chronologically on the single case","The agent must check three different tabs: Portal, Phone Log, Email Log"],ans:2,exp:"The Case Activity Stream (Timeline) in the Agent Workspace consolidates all interactions on a single case — portal updates, agent notes, inbound/outbound emails, and state changes — into one chronological view. This omnichannel consolidation on a single case record is a core CSM design principle."},
    {q:"A senior agent identifies a surge of cases about the same database error and wants to flag one for manager review as a potential major issue. Which step initiates this process?",opts:["The agent directly creates a Major Case from the case form","The agent marks the case as a major case candidate — a manager then reviews and approves it","The agent escalates the case using the Escalate Case UI action, which auto-promotes it to a Major Case","The agent runs a report and a scheduler auto-creates the Major Case"],ans:1,exp:"The Major Issue Management process starts when an agent identifies a case as a 'major case candidate' by setting the appropriate field on the case. This triggers an approval workflow where a manager decides whether to formally promote it to a Major Case. Direct creation without the candidate/approval step bypasses the governance process."},
    {q:"Which CSM feature automatically groups cases with similar content together using machine learning, helping managers identify recurring issue patterns before they become major incidents?",opts:["Case Digest","Predictive Intelligence — Trending Topics / Clustering","Major Issue Management candidate flagging","SLA breach reporting"],ans:1,exp:"Predictive Intelligence Trending Topics (also referred to as Clustering) automatically groups cases with similar characteristics using ML. This surfaces recurring issue patterns to managers — enabling proactive responses like creating knowledge articles or triggering a Major Case — before the volume becomes critical."}
  ],

  // ── D4: Workspace, Portals & Analytics (15 questions)
  [
    {q:"Which ServiceNow framework powers the CSM Configurable Workspace used by agents in 2026?",opts:["Service Portal (AngularJS)","Classic UI (GlideRecord forms)","Next Experience (Polaris UI Builder)","Employee Center (Unified Portal)"],ans:2,exp:"The CSM Configurable Workspace is built on the Next Experience framework and configured via UI Builder. The Customer Service Portal for external customers is built on Service Portal/AngularJS — these are separate frameworks and a common exam distractor."},
    {q:"What is the primary purpose of the Ribbon component in the CSM Configurable Workspace?",opts:["It displays SLA timer countdowns at the bottom of the screen","It is a horizontal strip at the top of the workspace providing quick access to key case fields and actions without scrolling","It shows incoming chat notifications from customers","It is a visual indicator of agent availability status"],ans:1,exp:"The Ribbon is a persistent horizontal component at the top of the Configurable Workspace that surfaces the most critical case fields (priority, state, SLA) and action buttons. Agents can act on key fields without scrolling down the full case form, improving efficiency."},
    {q:"In the CSM Configurable Workspace, what does the Agent Assist panel provide?",opts:["A direct messaging channel between agents","AI-powered suggestions including similar cases, knowledge articles, and recommendations surfaced in real time as the agent works a case","A list of agents currently available in the queue","A script that agents read aloud to customers during calls"],ans:1,exp:"Agent Assist is a contextual panel that uses machine learning to surface relevant knowledge articles, similar resolved cases, and suggested next actions in real time. It reduces handle time by bringing resolution resources directly to the agent without switching screens."},
    {q:"The Dynamic Related Records component in the CSM Configurable Workspace differs from a static Related List because:",opts:["It only shows records from external systems","It intelligently surfaces related records based on the current case context, without the agent manually navigating to them","It replaces the Activity Stream timeline","It is only visible to supervisors, not agents"],ans:1,exp:"Dynamic Related Records automatically determines which related records are relevant to the current case (same account open cases, related install base items, linked entitlements) and displays them contextually. Static related lists always show all records of a type regardless of relevance."},
    {q:"Customer Central in CSM provides agents with what capability?",opts:["A portal page where customers manage their own profile","A 360-degree view of a customer showing account details, all cases, entitlements, install base, and contacts from a single workspace screen","A reporting dashboard for customer satisfaction scores only","A bulk case assignment tool for managers"],ans:1,exp:"Customer Central is the 360-degree customer view in CSM. When an agent opens Customer Central for an Account, they see the full relationship: contact list, active entitlements, install base, all case history (open and closed), and account health indicators — without navigating across multiple modules.", diagram:"customer-central"},
    {q:"The Consumer Service Portal in ServiceNow CSM is designed primarily for which audience?",opts:["Internal IT agents resolving employee requests","B2C individual consumers who interact with a company's support without belonging to a corporate account","B2B contacts who work for enterprise customer accounts","ServiceNow administrators managing portal configuration"],ans:1,exp:"The Consumer Service Portal is tailored for B2C scenarios — individual consumers who need to submit cases, check status, and access self-service resources. It is separate from the Customer Service Portal, which serves B2B contacts, and is optimized for high-volume consumer interactions."},
    {q:"What is the purpose of Registration Codes in the CSM Customer Service Portal self-registration flow?",opts:["They are discount codes for purchasing products","Unique codes distributed to authorized customers that allow them to self-register on the portal, controlling who can create an account","They are temporary passwords sent to agents","They are license keys for activating CSM plugins"],ans:1,exp:"Registration Codes are alphanumeric tokens that administrators pre-generate and distribute to entitled customers (e.g., in a welcome email). When self-registering, the customer enters the code to prove they are authorized, preventing unauthorized account creation on the portal."},
    {q:"A company deploys the Customer Service Portal to customers in France, Germany, and Japan. Which portal capability ensures each customer sees the portal in their preferred language?",opts:["Separate ServiceNow instances per country","Portal locale and language settings — the portal detects browser language or lets users select their locale, serving translated content","Manual translation requests submitted to the admin team","The portal only supports English — localization requires custom development"],ans:1,exp:"Service Portal supports locale and language features out-of-the-box. Content can be translated using ServiceNow Translation Manager or i18n properties, and the portal can detect the user's browser language or allow manual selection, serving the appropriate translated UI and content."},
    {q:"On the Customer Service Portal, a customer wants to submit a formal request for a new service. Which Service Catalog object type is MOST appropriate for capturing structured data and creating a Case?",opts:["Order Guide","Content Item","Record Producer","Knowledge Article"],ans:2,exp:"A Record Producer is a Service Catalog item type that creates a record in a specified table (e.g., a Case) when submitted. It presents a form to the customer, captures structured input via variables, and creates the appropriate record — ideal for 'request a service' scenarios on the Customer Service Portal."},
    {q:"A company wants to offer walk-in support at retail locations where customers check in on a kiosk, join a queue, and are served by an in-store agent. Which ServiceNow CSM feature supports this?",opts:["Engagement Messenger embedded kiosk mode","Walk-Up Experience portal","CSM Field Service Management dispatch","Virtual Agent voice interface"],ans:1,exp:"Walk-Up Experience is a dedicated CSM feature for in-person support queues. Customers check in via a kiosk or portal, join a virtual queue, receive estimated wait times, and are called when an agent is ready. It is purpose-built for walk-in support center scenarios."},
    {q:"When comparing SLA Compliance Rate tracked as a Performance Analytics indicator versus a standard SLA report, what is the key advantage of the PA indicator?",opts:["PA indicators are the only way to view SLA data — standard reports cannot","A PA indicator tracks SLA compliance over time enabling trend analysis across periods, while a standard report shows only a current snapshot","Standard reports refresh automatically; PA indicators are static","PA indicators are only available to administrators"],ans:1,exp:"The core advantage of a PA SLA Compliance indicator over a standard report is historical trending — PA stores scores over time, enabling analysis of whether compliance is improving or worsening week-over-week and month-over-month. Standard reports reflect current data only and cannot natively trend KPI values."},
    {q:"A Performance Analytics dashboard shows a CSAT indicator in red. What does this mean?",opts:["The CSAT survey response rate is 0%","The CSAT score has fallen below the configured warning threshold, triggering the red alert color","There are no cases in the period","The PA data collection job has failed"],ans:1,exp:"In Performance Analytics, indicator colors reflect threshold breaches: green (on target), amber (approaching limit), red (below acceptable threshold). A red CSAT indicator means the score has dropped below the lower threshold set by the administrator, triggering a visual alert that action is needed."},
    {q:"An international company deploys Engagement Messenger on their product website. A logged-in customer clicks the support widget and their Account/Contact info is pre-populated automatically. What enables this?",opts:["The customer's browser cookie stores the ServiceNow session","Engagement Messenger uses a JWT passed from the host website to authenticate and identify the customer against their ServiceNow record","The customer must log in to ServiceNow separately first","Engagement Messenger reads the customer's email from browser autofill"],ans:1,exp:"Engagement Messenger supports authenticated sessions via JWT token exchange. The host website passes a signed JWT containing the customer's identity to Engagement Messenger, which validates it and resolves the customer to their Consumer or Contact record. This eliminates re-authentication and enables personalized support."},
    {q:"Which Performance Analytics feature allows breaking down a KPI metric such as First Contact Resolution rate by agent, group, or category?",opts:["Scorecard","Breakdown","Dashboard","Trend Report"],ans:1,exp:"The Breakdown feature in Performance Analytics allows analyzing KPI metrics along multiple dimensions — by agent, group, category, channel, or time period. It answers questions like 'Which team has the lowest FCR?' or 'Which channel generates the most volume?' — essential for targeted service improvement."},
    {q:"In UI Builder, when configuring the CSM Configurable Workspace, an administrator wants certain contextual side panel components to appear only for Gold-tier account cases. Which approach is correct?",opts:["Assignment Rule conditions on the side panel","Conditional visibility rules on the side panel components set within the Workspace Experience configuration in UI Builder","System Properties override for Gold accounts","Classic form personalization settings"],ans:1,exp:"In UI Builder, when configuring the Configurable Workspace Experience, administrators set conditional visibility rules on side panel components. Conditions can reference entitlement tier, account type, or case fields to tailor what appears in the panel — for example, showing a premium SLA tracker only for Gold accounts."}
  ],

  // ── D5: Knowledge Management & Best Practices (15 questions)
  [
    {q:"In KCS (Knowledge-Centered Service), which principle states that the value of knowledge is determined by how much it is used?",opts:["Knowledge is an asset","Demand drives supply","Knowledge is always evolving","Reuse is the measure of value"],ans:3,exp:"KCS principle 'Reuse is the measure of value' holds that an article's worth is proven by how often it successfully resolves customer issues. Articles that are never linked to resolved cases have unproven value, which drives the KCS practice of tracking article reuse metrics."},
    {q:"A knowledge article exists in 'In Review' state. A CSM agent finds it while working a case. Which statement is correct?",opts:["The agent can publish it immediately from the case","The article is visible to customers on the portal in read-only mode","The article is only accessible internally and not yet visible to customers","The article is automatically published after 24 hours in review"],ans:2,exp:"Articles in 'In Review' state are part of the internal approval workflow — they are visible only to internal users (agents, reviewers) and are NOT displayed on the Customer Service Portal. Only 'Published' articles appear to customers. This prevents unvalidated information from reaching customers."},
    {q:"What is the primary purpose of Knowledge Blocks (Symptom, Cause, Resolution) in ServiceNow CSM?",opts:["To restrict access to different sections of an article based on user role","To enforce a consistent structure so articles are actionable and searchable","To automatically translate articles into multiple languages","To split long articles into paginated sections for mobile display"],ans:1,exp:"Knowledge Blocks enforce the KCS-recommended Symptom-Cause-Resolution structure. This consistency makes articles easier to search, understand, and reuse — core KCS goals. Each block captures a distinct aspect: what the customer experienced, why it happened, and how it was fixed.", diagram:"knowledge-blocks"},
    {q:"An administrator wants to restrict a knowledge base so only customers with an active Enterprise entitlement can see its articles on the portal. Which mechanism controls this?",opts:["SLA definitions on the knowledge base","User Criteria applied to the knowledge base Can Read field","Assignment Groups linked to the knowledge base","A Business Rule on the kb_knowledge table"],ans:1,exp:"User Criteria in ServiceNow defines who can read, contribute, or own knowledge bases and articles. By creating User Criteria that checks for an active Enterprise entitlement and applying it to the knowledge base's 'Can Read' field, only qualifying customers can see the knowledge base on the portal."},
    {q:"Knowledge Product Entitlements in CSM allow administrators to:",opts:["Automatically create cases when a product's knowledge articles are viewed","Restrict which knowledge articles a customer can access based on the products they own","Grant agents knowledge authoring rights based on product expertise","Link knowledge articles directly to SLA definitions"],ans:1,exp:"Knowledge Product Entitlements tie article visibility to the products a customer owns (via Install Base Items or entitlements). A customer who owns Product X sees knowledge articles tagged for Product X; articles for products they do not own are hidden. This is more granular than simple User Criteria."},
    {q:"A company wants to surface articles from an external SharePoint site directly in the ServiceNow Knowledge Management search results. Which integration feature supports this?",opts:["REST API polling via a Scheduled Script","WebDAV external content integration","CMDB discovery connector","MID Server file sync"],ans:1,exp:"ServiceNow Knowledge Management supports WebDAV as an external content integration mechanism, allowing external repositories (such as SharePoint or other WebDAV-compliant systems) to be indexed and surfaced in ServiceNow knowledge search results. This avoids duplicating content that already exists externally."},
    {q:"In the Now Create methodology, which phase immediately follows the 'Initiate' phase?",opts:["Execute","Deliver","Plan","Close"],ans:2,exp:"Now Create's five phases in sequence are: Initiate > Plan > Execute > Deliver > Close. 'Plan' follows Initiate and covers sprint planning, backlog creation, and resource allocation. 'Execute' is the iterative build phase with workshops and sprints. Confusing the order is a common exam trap.", diagram:"nowcreate-phases"},
    {q:"During which Now Create phase do CSM configuration workshops and iterative build sprints occur?",opts:["Initiate","Plan","Execute","Deliver"],ans:2,exp:"The 'Execute' phase is where the actual implementation work happens — configuration workshops, sprint-based builds, and iterative testing. Initiate covers project kickoff and scoping; Plan covers backlog and resource planning; Deliver covers UAT and go-live. Execute is the longest and most intensive phase."},
    {q:"In Now Create, what is the purpose of an 'exit gate' between phases?",opts:["A formal sign-off confirming deliverables are complete before moving to the next phase","A performance review for the implementation team","A customer survey sent at each phase boundary","An automated ServiceNow workflow that locks the project record"],ans:0,exp:"Exit gates in Now Create are formal checkpoints at the end of each phase. Stakeholders and the project team confirm that all phase deliverables are complete and accepted before proceeding to the next phase. This prevents scope creep and ensures each phase builds on a solid foundation."},
    {q:"A company is deploying CSM in a phased release approach. Which of the following BEST describes this strategy?",opts:["Deploying all functionality to all users on a single go-live date","Releasing functionality incrementally — e.g., one channel or one region at a time — to reduce risk and allow learning","Developing in waterfall and testing all at once before any release","Deploying to production without testing to get customer feedback quickly"],ans:1,exp:"A phased release approach rolls out CSM incrementally — for example, launching the email channel first, then portal, then chat; or going live in one region before expanding globally. This reduces go-live risk, allows the team to address issues gradually, and gives agents time to adapt before full rollout."},
    {q:"Which of the following is an example of CONFIGURATION in ServiceNow CSM (as opposed to customization)?",opts:["Adding a new column to the case table via a custom database extension","Writing a Script Include to override the default case assignment algorithm","Creating a new Assignment Rule using the OOTB Assignment Rules module","Modifying core ServiceNow JavaScript files to change platform behavior"],ans:2,exp:"Configuration uses out-of-the-box tools (Assignment Rules, Business Rules with standard conditions, UI Policies, etc.) without altering base platform code. Customization involves modifying or extending the platform beyond standard capabilities. The CIS-CSM exam strongly emphasizes configuration over customization."},
    {q:"Now Assist for CSM Sentiment Analysis helps CSM teams by:",opts:["Automatically closing cases where sentiment is positive","Detecting the emotional tone of customer messages and surfacing at-risk cases to supervisors","Translating customer messages in real time to the agent's language","Calculating CSAT scores without requiring customer surveys"],ans:1,exp:"Sentiment Analysis in Now Assist for CSM uses AI to detect the emotional tone (positive, neutral, negative) of customer messages. When negative sentiment is detected, the system can surface these cases to supervisors or trigger escalation workflows — enabling proactive intervention before customers become more upset."},
    {q:"Which 2026 ServiceNow AI feature uses machine learning to automatically group similar cases into clusters, helping managers identify recurring issue patterns?",opts:["Now Assist Case Summarization","Predictive Intelligence — Clustering","Process Mining","Continual Improvement Management (CIM)"],ans:1,exp:"Predictive Intelligence Clustering automatically groups cases with similar characteristics (category, description, resolution) into clusters. This helps managers identify recurring issue patterns, knowledge gaps, and product defects. It is distinct from PI Classification (which assigns individual cases to categories) and Process Mining (which analyzes workflow patterns)."},
    {q:"How does Continual Improvement Management (CIM) integrate with ServiceNow CSM?",opts:["CIM automatically closes CSM cases after 30 days","CIM allows CSM teams to create formal improvement initiatives triggered by CSM performance data and track them through a structured improvement lifecycle","CIM replaces Performance Analytics for CSM reporting","CIM is only available in ITSM and cannot connect to CSM"],ans:1,exp:"CIM integrates with CSM by allowing managers to spin up structured improvement initiatives from CSM performance data. For example, a surge in Password Reset cases triggers a CIM improvement item to streamline the self-service process. CIM provides the structured workflow to drive and track those improvements."},
    {q:"A knowledge article published 2 years ago has been used 450 times successfully. An agent realizes the resolution steps are now outdated due to a software upgrade. According to KCS, what is the CORRECT action?",opts:["Create a brand-new article and leave the old one published","Flag the article for retirement and create a duplicate","Edit the existing article in place, updating the Resolution block, and route it through review before republishing","Delete the article immediately to prevent customers from using the wrong steps"],ans:2,exp:"KCS encourages evolving knowledge in place — update the existing high-reuse article rather than creating duplicates or deleting it. The agent should update the Resolution block, which triggers a review workflow (returning the article to 'In Review' for approval before republishing). This preserves the article's reuse history while ensuring accuracy."}
  ]
];
